Loaded memory
After more than 60 years in a confidential regime, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which recount the fates of the 17.5 million victims of Hitler's regime, are open to the public.
So long, 47 million archival documents stored over a length of 27 km in Bad Arolsen (Hesse) have been accessible until now only for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and specifically, at the request of the former victim or her beneficiaries.
Eleven states charged with managing the archives - including Germany, France, Israel, and the United States - agreed in May to open them to scientists and historians.
As the process of ratifying this agreement by all states is over, the opening took effect yesterday.
Sensitive information
Free access by historians to Bad Arolsen will allow to examine "especially the movements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the state of health of the forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (Comité international de la Croix-rouge, CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, were opposed to making these nominal documents available to the public because of the sensitive nature of some information.
Such as the expected homosexuality or mental disability of some deportation victims.
Registers of concentration camps or arrest warrants compiled by the Gestapo were collected after the war for the practical purpose of finding deported or forced labor subjected to civilians, bringing them proof of their internment in order to open the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees in Bad Arolsen are engaged in tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited benefit.
"Nothing fundamentally new can be expected from these documents," Prof. Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for the Study of Anti-Semitism at Berlin's Technische Universität, said in 2006.
