Congress approves MiFID transposing from November 1
In parallel with the parliamentary negotiations that ended today with a congressional vote on amendments incorporated by the Senate into the bill, the government has subjected a public hearing to an order developing a new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
Party leaders agreed on the efforts of members and senators to negotiate and agree the best standard to guarantee investor protection and detailed regulation of the activities of entities needed for the efficient functioning of markets.
The MiFID Directive, which is regulated by the Securities Trading Act, envisages the modernisation of financial markets while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the State Securities Market Commission (CNMV) and supporting cooperation between the various supervisory bodies of the European Union.
This new regulation will enable financial advice services to be provided to both specialised firms and natural or legal persons and creates a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (AFI) that join securities companies, securities intermediary offices and portfolio management companies.
In addition, the number of systems for the performance of operations with financial instruments is increasing by connecting multilateral trading and order internalisation systems to regulated secondary markets to compete with current stockbrokers.
Furthermore, the act obliges investment services firms to disseminate information on key aspects of their business profile, exposure to risk and risk management methods on the market and requires a statement of all operations carried out to simplify supervision by the CNMV.
During the congressional commerce committee hearing, several modifications were included, including that securitised claims be considered a "complex" financial instrument given the high risk to investors that has been demonstrated by what happened in the US with high-risk mortgage debt (subprime).
Moreover, the transposing of the Directive has been used to legally set out the functions that bachelors in ecocommy and corporate governance can hold 30 years after the adoption in 1977 of a royal decree outshoting professional functions reserved for economists.
At the same time, the Senate included the creation of new professions in the financial sector, such as an intermediary that will work externally, will not require permission from the CNMV and will be able to provide product trading services and client acquisition services for various investment firms at the same time.
