Fears of a new gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A dispute over gas prices is currently underway between Russia and Ukraine, increasing the risk that Russian supplies of this fuel to Western Europe may be affected.
Most of the Russian fuel exported to the European Union (EU) is routed through Ukraine, and any dispute between the two countries is closely watched.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow raises gas prices for Ukraine, it will charge Russia higher transit fees.
A previous dispute between the two last year reduced supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes as the Ukrainian government and Russia's state-owned gas monopoly, Gazprom, try to agree on how much Ukraine will have to pay for Russian gas in 2008.
Gazprom says it will have to charge Ukraine more because it has agreed to pay up to 50% more for the gas it receives from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say this could mean Ukraine will have to pay 40% more for its supplies from Gazprom.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states during the negotiations," Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinach told Reuters.
"Changes in gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the level of transit charges (to Western Europe) through Ukraine."
The last major dispute between Moscow and Kiev caused gazprom's supply to ukraine to be reduced in January 2006.
This caused a crushing fall in exports to Western Europe, which sharply increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of supplies to the European Union.
Russia has the largest gas reserves in the world, but much of it remains underutilized.
As a result, Gazprom is replenishing its own gas supplies from Turkmenistan and other former Soviet Central Asian republics.
