Climate on Venus may be a glimpse into earth's future
Scientists announced yesterday that Venus may once have been a pleasant place to live.
Data from a orbiting European station shows that the planet is even more similar to Earth's willful twin than previously thought.
Venus is Earth's closest planetary neighbor.
These two worlds are roughly the same size and orbit similar paths, but Venus is a little closer to the sun.
Scientists now believe that billions of years ago, conditions on Venus were similar to those on Earth and could have been habitable.
But the runaway greenhouse effect caused by carbon dioxide, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation, and a lower rate of rotation sent Venus down a completely different path of development.
Today, the planet is without water, the surface temperature is hot enough to melt lead, and it's ravaged by storms and hurricane-force winds.
The findings from the European Space Agency's Venus Express probe, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a spate of how the Earth could evolve in the event of catastrophic climate change.
Professor Fred Taylor, from Oxford University's Department of Physics and one of the heads of the Venus Express mission, said: "It is becoming increasingly clear why the climate on Venus is so different from on Earth, even though the planets themselves are otherwise quite similar.
"Our new data makes it possible to build a scenario in which Venus began, like Earth, perhaps even with a habitable environment, billions of years ago."
