The two struggled particularly fiercely when interviewers asked if any of the candidates would support an "amnesty" (to give illegal immigrants a normal status and citizenship).
Minor candidates like Duncan Hunter, a California congressman, and Tom Tancredo, a congressman from Colorado, were able to throw their little bit into the mill on the subject.
None of the two stand a chance of being nominated, but both remain in the game perhaps because they started sounding the alarm about immigration sooner and harder than the others.
At least on immigration, the candidates have roughly the same view: greater austerity at the border, no tolerance for illegal migrants.
This issue, along with concerns about poisonous toys from China and other worries about the outside world, helps Republicans forget or minimize the divide between libertaries and Christian conservatives.
But the debate got very uncomfortable when it came to other topics.
Mr Giuliani was asked why he had supported firearms possession in the past.
John McCain and Mr Romney discussed whether simulated heating techniques should be considered torture.
One questioner asked if the candidates believed every word in the Bible.
Mr. Giuliani stumbled through it to the point that, even though the Bible is his favorite book, he probably doesn't literally believe the story of Jonah and the whale after all.
Another questioner asked if Jesus would support the death penalty.
Mike Huckabee - who is now at the top of all assumptions in a recent Iowa poll because of his longstanding Christian conservatism - said the death penalty is unpleasant but necessary.
Pressed on whether Jesus would agree, he said Jesus was too smart to run, earning him a laugh.
The fight remains unusually open.
Mr. Huckabee's surge in Iowa coincides with recent fundraising successes and Ron Paul's loud cheers at Wednesday's debate.
These two have bounced back because both wings of the party still cannot agree on more familiar and traditional candidates.
In 1980 and 2000, one of the candidates united the party very early and convincingly with a winning message about American greatness on his lips, blinking at both wings of the party.
This time, the party is divided, and the result is far from clear.
Labour's Pains
Gordon Brown again found a trap to fall into; his way out remains the same.
Although it is customary in British political scandals, this one is not particularly spicy.
No orders seem to have been sold, no bills at the Paris hotel have been mysteriously paid, no extramarital fingers have been sucked in.
But a barricaded Gordon Brown would have done without discovering that some wealthy businessman had masked contributions to the ruling Labor Party of £650,000 ($1.3 million) under other people's names for four years, and that the party had not reported it.
Two months ago, when the Prime Minister avoided calling an election and insulted British intelligence by claiming that the decision was not influenced by the polls, there was hope that he would ensure a resilient and effective government.
Instead, as the increasingly funny deputy leader of the Liberal Democrats put it, the once-feared Mr Brown went from Stalin to Mr Bean.
The clumsy rescue of troubled bank Northern Rock showed weaknesses in management and poor judgment under fire.
Ill-thought-out proposals to change the tax code brought companies together against the government.
The loss of personal data to 25 million people revealed unimaginable administrative bedity.
A trio of retired generals started a rebellion in the House of Lords; they protested against cuts in military spending, claiming that being commander of the armed forces was a part-time job.
Now there are many gifts from David Abrahams; Peter Watt, Labour's general secretary (and their former internal discipline watchdog), has already resigned.
None of this means that Mr. Brown is inevitably heading towards his end.
Despite this, governments can reach a tipping point that they find difficult to govern.
People don't trust politicians and don't like them, but they usually shift their distrust when a new group takes over.
When it seems clear that a prime minister is unlikely to improve anything, and may not be in office for long, this is a push away: the civil service is becoming leaky, ministers are starting to do briefings, the press is looking for bad news, and the government is becoming unfocused and defensive.
In one respect, Mr. Brown's position is particularly difficult, because he cannot take the position of a new broom compared to other political leaders.
As much as he would like to distance himself from Tony Blair, he was his first officer.
For example, the problems with Northern Rock and the IRS records are linked to the decisions Mr Brown made as Finance Minister.
And even if he was not directly involved in Blairite troubles, such as a long investigation into the financing of political parties caused by "ranks for money," voters may well think he was.
Yet Mr. Brown's peddling isn't as bad as it looks.
These mistakes aren't as terrible as the Conservatives are doing.
As far as Mr. Bean is concerned, no one has died or been outright deceived.
And the treatment, painful as it may be, is to provide what Mr. Brown's Stalinist tendencies have always promised: a reliable, firm, and slightly brutal government.
The latest uproar over political donations is a good example.
Garboid Mr Abrahams, who compares his donations to charity, says he did not want any publicity for his charity.
That may be true, but it wasn't his decision to make.
The laws against the anonymity of large political donors are clear and exist for a simple reason: the public has a right to know who might buy access to those who rule the country.
Mr Watt, who said he knew about Mr Abrahams' progress but did not know it was illegal, will certainly be thoroughly questioned; so did Jon Mendlesohn, labour's chief money-raiser, who learned of the tricky donations in October.
But so far, Mr. Brown is not involved; there is nothing to suggest that he knew about these plots, even though the main part of the payments took place only after his arrival in June.
So far, the Prime Minister has done half the work.
He was quick to condemn this violation by his own party, but he diluted his resolve by reaching for a proven instrument, a commission to investigate the matter - led by a retired bishop and a judge.
In this case, the lessons are not complicated.
If the law has been broken, it's a police matter.
There are also other things that Mr Brown needs to do, such as finding a permanent chairman of the independent Committee on Standards in Public Life, which has had none for six months, and making progress with a real reform of party funding.
This would require Labour, which is in a tight spot, to work with the Conservatives and perhaps give up their special financial relationship with the unions - a bitter pill for a dedicated party member like Mr Brown.
But he should face a few simple facts.
The Conservatives now have a decent lead in the polls; he has two years to win back the electorate; and the only way to win is with unassailable integrity and high integrity.
Card Sharks
Is the sub-mortgage crisis affecting the US credit card market?
When there is blood in the water, naturally the dorsal fins begin to smourdev excitedly around.
Now that the US real estate market is withering, predators have focused on the credit card market there.
Goldman Sachs analysts say credit card losses could reach $99 billion if other variants of consumer credit become infected from sub-sub-mortgages.
The signs of tension are palpable.
There is an increasing number of default cases (with more than 30 days of payment delay) and written-off accounts (accounts that the provider considers unenforceable).
HSBC announced last month that it had lost $1.4bn in the US consumer credit market - also due to insolvent credit card loans.
But it is too early to panic.
Written-off bills and inability to repay are still scarce.
According to moody's, the 3.89% insolvency rate in the third quarter was almost a full percentage point below average.
The deteriorating rates can be partly explained by technical reasons.
A change in us personal bankruptcy laws in 2005 led to a sharp decline in the number of reported bankruptcies, which account for a large part of credit card losses; the number of reports (and thus the number of depreciations) would therefore increase regardless of whether the general conditions for borrowers have deteriorated.
The sector also has a good maturity rate, which shows how much consumers pay off their debts each month.
And confidence in credit card-backed securities is solid, despite paralysis in other corners of structured finance.
Dennis Moroney of towergroup, a research firm, predicts that their emissions for 2007 will be 25% higher than last year.
There are certainly direct ways to spread the infection between the sub-mortgage crisis and the credit card market: when real estate equity loans run out, consumers are more likely to get into debt through credit cards.
But credit card issuers are looking at cash flow rather than the value of guaranteed items, so falling home prices do not necessarily mean a change in borrowers' credibility.
They may even be advantageous for lenders.
Consumers' incentives to pay off their mortgages decrease when the value of their assets falls below the value of the loan; as a result, the debt on the cards moves up the list of repayment priorities.
Card issuers can also respond faster and more flexibly to stormier conditions than mortgage providers by changing interest rates or debt limits.
This should, in theory, reduce the risks of a rapid change in the prices of the guarano items.
"It's not going to happen that one beautiful morning we just rethink all the loans," says Gary Perlin, chief financial manager at Capital One.
While the risk of sub-mortgage-style explosions is low, the risk of gradual weakening is far more real.
If lower house prices and debt reduction push America into recession, the credit card industry will be in for a darker future.
Watch out for those dorsal fins.
British bankers plead guilty in Enron case
Three British bankers to stand trial for their roles in a fraud related to enron's former chief financial manager Andrew Fastow changed their story on Wednesday and pleaded guilty.
David Bermingham, Giles Darby and Gary Mulgrew originally pleaded guilty to seven counts of fraud, in which he and Fastow were to participate in a financial fraud in 2000 -- enriching themselves at the expense of their employers -- they denied.
They were due to stand trial in January.
However, during the trial before U.S. District Judge Ewing Werlein Jr., each pleaded guilty to one count of fraud.
The case of the three former executives of Greenwich NatWest, a unit of Royal Bank of Scotland Group PLC, made headlines for the two years that lasted.
In the United States, their case is one of the unseen parts of an investigation launched after the 2001 Enron crash.
The charges against them in 2002 alerted Mr. Fastow that he was the target of a government investigation into the Enron crash.
The indictment against the bankers -- who earned the nickname "NatWest Three" -- alleges that they came to Houston in 2000 to plot the scam along with Fastow and his former chief aide, Michael Kopper.
Greenwich NatWest invested in a partner subsidiary of Enron controlled by Fastow, who was the architect of a series of Enron scams that pushed Enron down a spiral toward bankruptcy.
At the beginning of 2002, the bank valued its stake in this branch at zero, but our three Britons knew that it was actually worth a great deal.
The company under Kopper's control bought the bank's stake in the branch for $1 million.
The incriminating bankers paid Kopper $250,000 for a stake in the company.
According to the indictment, Fastow misled Enron that the energy company would pay $20 million for its stake in the Greenwich NatWest subsidiary.
But the $20 million actually went to those British bankers, Fastow and others.
According to the indictment, the bankers received $7.3 million, and Fastow, Kopper and others added about $12.3 million.
In January 2004, Fastow pleaded guilty to two counts of conspiracy for his role in the collapse of Enron.
The British trio were arrested three months later.
Fastow is currently serving a six-year sentence in a federal prison in Louisiana.
Kopper is serving a sentence of three years and one month at a facility in Texarkana.
All three Britons were free on $1 million bail, which ordered them to remain in the United States for the upcoming trial.
Enron, once the country's seventh-largest company, went bankrupt in December 2001 after years of billing tricks that made it impossible to hide billions in debt or to show failing speculation as profitable.
The collapse has cut thousands of jobs, more than $60 billion in market value, and more than $2 billion in pensions.
Enron founder Kenneth Lay and former chief executive Jeffrey Skilling were convicted last year for their roles in the company's downfall.
Skilling is serving a sentence of more than 24 years.
Lay's convictions for conspiracy, fraud and other charges were overturned after he died of heart disease last year.
Moscow's non-helplessness
The price of a Gulfstream G550 aircraft equipped with a Rolls-Royce engine and enough fuel for a nonstop flight from Moscow to Los Angeles starts at $54 million.
For some of Russia's rich, however, it's small change to return.
"It can carry up to 18 passengers," says Dan Firer, a Gulfstream representative.
"But none of them are interested in that many places because it's for a close family or a corporate president."
Mr. Firer sat in the Gulfstream booth last Friday at the Millionaire's Show, a four-day of flamboyant consumerism at a mammoth exhibition center on the capital's periphery.
In addition to Gulfstream, more than 200 other luxury vendors built their stalls, hoping to lure newly wealthy Russians to everything from mahogany-inlaimed yachts to diamond-enlabelled car bulkheads that wouldn't be ashamed of 50 Cent.
Mr. Firer looked cautiously at the bright orange Porsche in the next stall.
"That's a nice car, but it's a dite and a dim against us," he said.
"After the United States, Russia is the second largest private jet market."
On the waves of oil, money is pouring into the Russian capital, just like when Dallas had its days.
"We went through the same stage in the 1980s when some Americans got hugely rich and went to Europe, where they were seen as materialists," said Marshall Goldman, a fourth-year student at harvard's Davis Center for Russian and Eurasian Studies.
Like the Saudi spenders of the 1970's and the Japanese of the 1990's, Russians are becoming the world's most profitable spenders.
The most exclusive luxury brands are looking for their share of this Klondike.
Elsewhere in Moscow this week, a conference of luxury industry attracted Donatella Versace, Tom Ford and Bernard Arnault, chairman of LVMH, to exchange ideas on how to sell expensive goods in markets like Russia's.
(The conference is organized by The International Herald Tribune, owned by The New York Times Company.)
Russia has 53 billionaires with a total fortune of $282 billion, according to Forbes magazine's list of the richest people.
Moreover, the local main institute in the field of Center for Economic and Financial Research has published a report on the development of personal wealth in the former Soviet Union, according to which there are 103,000 "second-class" millionaires in Russia, whose wealth totals $670 billion.
(The World Bank reports that in 2005, 15.8% of Russians lived below the existential minimum.)
"There are hundreds of millionaires in Moscow -- and that's why we're all here," said Nicole Marais, sales and marketing representative for London jewelry store David Morris.
She was at the fair for the first time, together with the Russian distributor of this brand, Soho Jewelry Group.
"All women are immaculate, and men are worth a fortune."
As they strolled through the halls in their evening dresses on Sunday evening, Evgenia Yumatova, 21, and Svetlana Turovcova, five years older, described themselves and their clients as millionaires.
"I've been looking at these cars, and I can't decide between Infiniti, Mercedes and Porsche," said Ms. Yumatova, who was wearing designer clothes like a red carpet veteran who made Joan Rivers look like a house-topper.
The fair seemed aimed primarily at the freshly wealthy, brand-driven Russian shoppers who are willing to sit out a few hours on the road to sting around the warehouse, which blatantly mixes Cadillacs Escalade, platinum fish, Mövenpick ice cream, custom-made billiard tables, Dubai apartments, Gund stuffed animals and drafts.
Members of the general public could buy tickets for 30 euros ($44.57).
"Russians are interested in which brand is the most expensive and the best," said Mr. Gijrath, who patriotically occupied the stand of Dutch porcelain manufacturer Royal Delft before reproducing Rembrandt's painting of hand-painted blue embarotes in larger-than-life size.
"Of course, the Russians are more interested in tinsel."
Indeed, local vendors say that Russians with old money (10 to 15 years old by Russian standards) have moved from flashy logos to little-known limited-edition brands that would never show up at a shopping fair.
Even so, several thousand people, whether millionaires, millionaires' ambassadors or simple tourists, flooded the fair halls day after day.
And some of them were shopping.
On the first day of the exhibition, last Thursday, Roman Ershov, king koil's local general manager of beds, said he sold two mattress sets of silk, cashmere and cotton, interwoven with gold threads, for $70,000 each.
Also on the first day, Mikhail Lyubimov, sales manager at A1 Moto, which equips high-end cars with high-end alarms, said his company sold a bright orange Porsche for $170,000 to a Russian millionaire.
On Sunday afternoon, Andrei Karapetian, president of L.A. Connection, a luxury car company, said he sold three car grilles in the style of connected chain bracelets for $55,000 Rolls-Royce Phantoms.
He showed a reporter a car bike designed for a Russian casino owner that had a swadd of Swarovkian crystals so that it looked like roulette.
Price: $22,000 for four of those.
"The Russian millionaire who wants ostrich leather bikes or a portrait of his wife made of cubic zirkonia doesn't have to ride those bikes yet," Mr. Karapetian said.
"He'll store them in his garage of 30 to 40 cars."
Although many of his Russian clients are wealthy, Mr. Karapetian said that the phrase "Russian millionaire" does not mean much exclusive at the moment, given the large increase in the price of local real estate.
"If you bought an apartment in Moscow three or four years ago, you're probably already millionaires, at least on paper, if not in cash," he said.
"There are more of them than you think."
Those who are not millionaires could at least fake wealth at a booth run by Alliance Continental, a Russian asset management firm.
The company erected four British-style red phone booths stuffed with columns of fake million-dollar bills.
Azad Karryev, the company's marketing manager, said his team printed 500,000 fake bills for the Millionaires' Fair.
Passersby stopped to throw around a pile of money, or to get their mobile phone pictures taken by friends, resting in the middle of spare wealth, or simply stuffing a pocket of a few million.
"You know, in Moscow, everyone can feel like a millionaire," Mr. Karryev said.
Death in New Jersey may have been caused by botched surgery
It was the day before Thanksgiving when Roland Livingston looked a little healthier from the large windows of the local restaurant and watched the ambulance arrive at the white New England house two houses down West Scott Avenue.
Soon, a police patrol car joined in.
And then another one.
"Then I saw the medical examiner's van arrive," said Mr. Livingston, the restaurant inspector.
"That's when I knew someone had died."
Authorities learned that the dead woman was Olga Arroya, 41, executive assistant director of the New York Police Department.
Now investigators are trying to determine if she died because of a procedure done by an unlicensed plastic surgeon whose identity police declined to provide, who worked at the 212 west scott avenue home.
Authorities have yet to determine what caused Ms. Arroyo's death, and they hope toxicology tests, the results of which may not be known for weeks, will help solve the mysterious death that sent a wave of grief through the New York Police Department.
Ms. Arroyo had been assistant to the police chief, Garry F. McCarthy, since September 2006, and her voice was familiar to many in the department.
