Hopes that the Fed will cut interest rates lead to a strengthening of the world's stock exchanges
Stock prices on both sides of the Atlantic jumped yesterday after the market's hopes that the Federal Reserve would try to calm lending conditions by cutting interest rates further were boosted by reassuring statements from the US central bank's vice chairman.
Stock markets jumped in London, New York and across Europe after Donald Kohn, second only to Ben Bernanke, chairman of the Fed, said that executives must be "flexible and pragmatistic" in responding to continued pressure in financial markets.
In an apparent effort to calm irritated markets amid signs of resuping credit efforts, Mr. Kohn said that recent upsurges "have partially reversed some of the improvements in the functioning of markets at the end of September and October."
He also said that if the increased instability persists, the possibility of financial conditions for households and businesses worsening will increase.
Investors see these statements as a signal that the Fed is ready to deliver more fresh doses of capital to US markets, and possibly further interest rate cuts to stabilize credit conditions.
The remarks also helped calm Wall Street amid further bad news about the US economy, with apartment sales showing record lows in October.
The consequences of the financial swirl were underlined by the announcement by the investment bank Bear Stearns that it would cut 650 jobs, or 4% of its global workforce, as part of cost-cutting to offset heavy losses caused by a failed bet on providing sub-market home loans in America.
Only 20 of these sites are expected to be closed in London, where the bank employs 1,500 people.
In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 331 points, or 2.55 percent, to close at 13,289.40, while the more-used S&P 500 gained 2.65 percent.
London's FTSE 100 index gained 165.5 points, or 2.7 percent, to close at 6,306.2, with the value of British blue-chips rising by more than £39 billion.
Germany's Dax index rose 2.6 percent and France's CAC40 gained 2.3 percent.
Some time ago, credit tensions in the markets proved to be in full force after these funds were lent to European commercial banks at a rate of 4.7% in the Auction of the European Central Bank's three-month cash packages, the highest since April 2001.
Pressure on the Bank of England to follow the Fed and the ECB and release above-standard money into London's money markets has increased as rates on three-month British interbank lending "Libor" have risen to their highest since late September - 6.59 percent - after uninterrupted growth since November 12.
