Buses bring refugees back to work - and to fight al-Qaeda
The first buses full of Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, emusing refugees who had run out of money or had expired visas, and others hoping the city would return to normal life.
Some even returned to fight the militants who drove them from their homes.
Mansour's bus station was already full of refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport before 800 people arrived from Damascus in an official government convoy of a dozen buses.
"I decided to go to Syria after many doctors were killed in Baghdad," said Sabah al-Kubaysi, a Sunni doctor.
"I came back today because of what I saw on TV and what I read about in the papers, because of what was going on in Baghdad and how safe it is now.
"They say the Mahdi army has stopped killing people," he said, referring to the Shiite militia of militant cleric Muktada al-Sadr, who temporarily ordered his people to stop fighting.
Kasim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite teacher from the predominantly Sunni Amariya region, returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visas and because the regime there did not allow Iraqis to work.
His Shiite neighbors in Amarija called him, saying that a local militia backed by the U.S. military had helped push al-Qaeda out of its positions in the west of the capital, urging him to return.
One of the new arrivals from Jordan is the leader of a Sunni and Shia tribe driven from his home in Sleich, northern Baghdad, by a grenade attack after urging his fellow citizens to rise up against al-Qaeda.
He came back to fight.
"A day ago, several friends called me and told me that he was starting an anti-al-Qaeda militia in Sleich and that he needed me and the support of my boy.
That's why I came back today," said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many spoke of the attraction of calm in the capital after the strengthening of america's military presence and the growth of local "groups of biased citizens" who, at gunpoint alongside the US military, are defending their neighborhoods.
But there was more talk of being forced to return by visa filibustering and the loss of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarraj, a 51-year-old father of three, voiced suspicions shared among refugees that Nuri al-Maliki, the Shiite prime minister, had asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugee visas to force them to return.
According to available data, more than two and a half million people have fled Iraqi sectarian killers.
"Everything was fine before al-Maliki visited Syria and pressured the government to stop giving Iraqis visas so they had to go back to Iraq," the Sunni pensioner said.
"I can't trust a government that supports criminals who burned down my house after I left."
Part of the reason for the weakening of violence is that Sunnis have been pushed out of Shiite areas, and vice versa, reducing tensions in many places.
There are fears that the sudden influx of refugees will re-instune sectarian tensions and lead to further fighting.
Tiny Saarland, good education
Germany's smallest land plays a leading role in vocational education, excelled even in the international focus of its universities.
In only one educational area, Saarland is concerned about the same deficiency as the rest of Germany.
"I explained to a non-Saarland man yesterday for the 50th time that we are not French" - this self-irony slogan appears on posters in Saarland to mark the 50th anniversary of the country's 50th birthday.
At the same time, France and Luxembourg play a major role in the Saar-based education system, which is in fifth place in the monitoring of education at the Cologne Institute for Economic Research (IW).
Universities have traditionally cooperated closely with neighbouring countries.
The University of Saarbrücken was founded by the French in 1948.
To this day, students can finish their studies here with a double or even triple diploma.
This corresponds to a reasonably high proportion of foreign students, which is 15.6%.
After all, an above-average number of Saarland children are admitted to university - many of them even without studying at a grammar school.
"The professional education system is used in Saarland," says Axel Plünnecke, an IW education expert.
By getting more than one in five teenagers authorized to study at a vocational school, Saarland is more than 7% above the German average.
Compared to the rest of Germany, there are rich possibilities in Saarland to combine practical and academic education.
The possibilities of studying two fields are the second best in germany in terms of population.
Despite practically oriented education and rising demand, the number of engineering graduates has fallen by a third in recent years.
That is why the Saarland Ministry of Education has now ordered universities to create a promotional campaign for engineering disciplines.
"After the first Pisa study, we made several reforms in general education schools," says a spokesman for the Ministry of Education.
The Government has therefore introduced comparative tests throughout Germany.
