These aren't Warhol's boxes.
Whoever combines the terms Sweden with wooden boxes thinks not of Andy Warhol, but of Ikea.
Don't you?
Wooden boxes currently produced in Sweden cast dark shadows on warhol's list of works.
Most of his list of ninety-four Stockholm -type "Brillo boxes" are forgeries.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" expressed doubts a few months ago about the authenticity of Warhol's "Brillo boxes" from 1968, internal research by the Moderna Museet museum in Stockholm comes with a result that has brought disillusionment; The six "Brillo boxes" donated to the Moderna Museet museum in 1995 by its former director Pontus Hultén are copies - as are most of the other Stockholm-type "Brillo boxes" that are in circulation on the international art market.
Previous events are a tangled, confusing chain of artistic and curatorial events.
Warhol made his first Brillo boxes in New York in 1964, painting wooden boxes that were based on the red-and-white design of brillo soap powder paper boxes.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet in 1968 showed - with Warhol's approval - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard. These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but were delivered directly from the Brillo factory.
These were not works of art, but their originals, mere exhibition pieces.
Warhol apparently also gave permission in 1968 to make several wooden Brillo boxes in Sweden, but these are not on display at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses at the time now speak of fifteen boxes that rightly entered art and auction history at that time as authorized originals - "Andy Warhol's Brillo Boxes" with the designation Type Stockholm.
Some of them were auctioned for more than $100,000.
The problem now is that the museum's legendary director, Pontus Hultén, later falsely claimed that in 1968, about 100 boxes were made and displayed in Sweden, which Warhol then left to him.
In fact, 105 of Hultén's boxes were made in Malmö for exhibition in St. Petersburg only in 1990.
By then, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, the chief conservator of moderna museet, examined, in addition to the six Brillo boxes owned by the museum, three Brillo boxes from a Swedish private collection, two of which were made in Sweden in 1968 and were painted oily white with a brush after their plywood slabs were painted with prime paint and polished.
On the contrary, it turned out from the structure of the copies from 1990 that the paint was applied directly to the plywood plate without a previous primer - in addition, it is acrylic and not oil paint.
"These boxes have not been authorised by the artist and should be removed from Warhol's official List of Brillo Boxes," said Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not reach any other conclusions, moderna museet will have to classify six boxes from its exhibition collections as "exhibition material - copies"."
As recently as July, the Authentication Board announced that it would look into the "core allegations" made about soap powder boxes.
But the organization still remains in relentless silence.
